{
  "text": "Although the results strongly suggest that postysnaptic 5-HT 1A receptor activity is necessary, neither acute administration of increasing doses of 8-OH-DPAT nor chronic administration of 1 mg/kg of 8-OH-DPAT (without additional fluoxetine) was effective in modifying the delay interval. In other delay of reward paradigms, the results obtained with 8-OH-DPAT have been variable. [CITATION_1] found that after administration of a 5-HT 1A receptor agonist (8-OH-DPAT), the rat seemed to become indifferent to reinforcement size or delay. [CITATION_2] found that 8-OH-DPAT had a biphasic effect. Low doses (0.006-0.03 mg/kg) of 8-OH-DPAT increased the choice of an immediate reinforcer, whereas a higher dose (0.06) increased the choice of a delayed reward. [CITATION_3] found that 8-OH-DPAT increased the choice of a larger delayed reward, but this effect was not antagonized by WAY100635. Thus, it would seem that although activity at the 5-HT 1A postsynaptic receptor may be necessary, it is an insufficient condition for reducing 'impulsive' behavior. The fact that WAY100635 had no significant effect on the length of the delay to reinforcement and seemed to suppress the effect of chronic fluoxetine supports this conclusion. Others also have reported that WAY100635 was either ineffective in delay of reward paradigms [CITATION_4] , or, at a very large dose (4 mg/kg), reduced the number of choices of the large reward [CITATION_5] .",
  "citation_candidates": [
